[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(13) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Yet the Lord testified against Israel.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And Jehovah adjured Israel",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " . . . The verb means here, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "gave solemn warning,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "charge.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Kings 17:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it is repeated, with a cognate noun as object: “His testimonies which he testified against them;” or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "his charges ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e.,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " precepts) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "which he had given them.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "By all the prophets, and by all the seers.—The Hebrew text is, by the hand of all his prophets—namely, every seer. One or two MSS. and the Targum have prophet, instead of his prophets. The Syriac has “by the hand of all his servants the prophets, and all the seers.” The Vulg. and Arabic also have both nouns plural. Seers were such persons as, without belonging to the prophetic order, came forward in times of emergency upon a sudden Divine impulse. Thenius thinks Israel and Judah are mentioned together because the reference is to the time before the partition of the kingdom; more probably, because both apostatised, and prophets were sent to both.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "By all the prophets, and by all the seers.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The Hebrew text is, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "by the hand of all his prophets",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "namely, every seer.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " One or two MSS. and the Targum have ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "prophet,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " instead of ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "his prophets.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " The Syriac has “by the hand of all his servants the prophets, and all the seers.” The Vulg. and Arabic also have both nouns plural. Seers were such persons as, without belonging to the prophetic order, came forward in times of emergency upon a sudden Divine impulse. Thenius thinks Israel and Judah are mentioned together because the reference is to the time before the partition of the kingdom; more probably, because both apostatised, and prophets were sent to both.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And which I sent—i.e., the law which I sent. But—as according to later Jewish ideas, the prophets did not bring the Law, but only interpreted it—it seems better to understand with the Vulg. (“et sicut misi”) “and according to all that I sent to you (i.e., enjoined upon you) by my servants the prophets.”",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "And which I sent",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "i.e., the law",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " which I sent. But—as according to later Jewish ideas, the prophets did not bring the Law, but only interpreted it—it seems better to understand with the Vulg. (“et sicut misi”) “",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "and according to all",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " that I sent to you (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "i.e.,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " enjoined upon you) by my servants the prophets.”",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Kings 17:13",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Kings 17:13",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Yet the Lord testified against Israel — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Against their false worship, and all their impieties. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "By all the prophets, and by all the seers —",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " To whom he declared his mind by extraordinary revelations and visions, and by whom he published it, bearing witness from heaven to their doctrine, by eminent and glorious miracles. Abarbinel, in his commentary on these books, hath noticed one or more prophets in every king’s reign, both in Israel and Judah, from the time of Saul to Zedekiah, in whose time Jerusalem was laid desolate. The ten tribes had lately had among them two most singularly eminent for their zeal, courage, fidelity, and the wonders which they wrought, in the name of God, in confirmation of their divine mission and doctrine, namely, Elijah and Elisha: the latter of whom had been instrumental in rescuing them from their enemies sundry times, when all human means had failed, and their case appeared perfectly hopeless, and who had been mercifully continued to them, a faithful witness for God, and a burning and shining light, for about sixty years. And in the days of this very king, when Israel was carried away captive, they had Hoshea, Amos, Isaiah, and Micah. And in the days of the last king of Judah, when that tribe was carried captive, they had Jeremiah and Ezekiel. All these had made it their care to show both the kings and people their sins, and warn them of the fatal consequences of them; and to exhort, beseech, and urge them to turn from them, to the worship and service of the living and true God.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "17:7-23 Though the destruction of the kingdom of the ten tribes was but briefly related, it is in these verses largely commented upon, and the reasons of it given. It was destruction from the Almighty: the Assyrian was but the rod of his anger, Isa 10:5. Those that bring sin into a country or family, bring a plague into it, and will have to answer for all the mischief that follows. And vast as the outward wickedness of the world is, the secret sins, evil thoughts, desires, and purposes of mankind are much greater. There are outward sins which are marked by infamy; but ingratitude, neglect, and enmity to God, and the idolatry and impiety which proceed therefrom, are far more malignant. Without turning from every evil way, and keeping God's statutes, there can be no true godliness; but this must spring from belief of his testimony, as to wrath against all ungodliness and unrighteousness, and his mercy in Christ Jesus.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
